  "prompt": "I feel lost and I have lost faith in Islam, but not in God. Any advice or books I can read?",
  "response": "I'm sorry to hear you're feeling lost, but it's commendable that you still hold faith in God. Many people go through periods of doubt and questioning, and it can be an opportunity for deeper understanding and growth. Here are some suggestions to help you navigate this journey:\n\n---\n\n### **Books to Read**\n1. **\"Reclaim Your Heart\" by Yasmin Mogahed**  \n   - A thoughtful exploration of spiritual challenges, heartbreak, and rediscovering faith in God. It\u2019s written for those who feel disconnected or disillusioned.\n\n2. **\"The Road to Mecca\" by Muhammad Asad**  \n   - The autobiography of Leopold Weiss, a Jewish convert to Islam, who shares his intellectual and spiritual journey to faith.\n\n3. **\"Purification of the Heart\" by Hamza Yusuf**  \n   - Focuses on inner struggles and spiritual diseases of the heart, offering practical advice for healing and reconnecting with God.\n\n4. **\"Islam and the Destiny of Man\" by Gai Eaton**  \n   - A profound exploration of Islam\u2019s teachings and how they relate to the human condition, written in a way that resonates with seekers.\n\n5. **\"The Sealed Nectar\" by Safi-ur-Rahman al-Mubarakpuri**  \n   - A biography of the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) that may help you reconnect with the foundational aspects of Islam.\n\n6. **\"Lost Islamic History\" by Firas Alkhateeb**  \n   - A historical perspective on the rich and diverse legacy of Islamic civilization, which might inspire a renewed appreciation for the faith.\n\n---\n\n### **Practical Steps**\n1. **Reflect on Your Relationship with God**  \n   - Focus on your personal connection with Allah (SWT). Prayer, dua (supplication), and meditation can help you feel closer to Him, even if you\u2019re struggling with organized religion.\n\n2. **Seek Knowledge**  \n   - Engage with scholars, attend lectures, or listen to podcasts that address your doubts. Sometimes, questioning is a path to deeper understanding.\n\n3. **Talk to Someone You Trust**  \n   - Share your feelings with a mentor, imam, or a trusted friend who can provide guidance and support.\n\n4. **Take It Step by Step**  \n   - Don\u2019t rush to resolve everything at once. Faith is a journey, and it\u2019s okay to take time to rebuild your connection with Islam.\n\n5. **Focus on the Essentials**  \n   - Simplify your practice and focus on the core tenets of Islam: belief in One God, prayer, and good character. Sometimes, overcomplicating things can lead to confusion.\n\n---\n\n### **Remember**\nIt\u2019s okay to question and doubt\u2014it\u2019s a natural part of seeking truth. Allah (SWT) knows your struggles and appreciates your sincerity. In the Quran, Allah says:  \n*\u201cAnd those who strive for Us\u2014We will surely guide them to Our ways. And indeed, Allah is with the doers of good.\u201d* (Quran 29:69)\n\nMay Allah guide you to peace, clarity, and a stronger connection with Him. You\u2019re not alone in this journey.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
